The specimens were collected in a stream and a wadeable river (Fig. 
8
) at a range of altitudes (
355-475 m
a.s.l.). Mae Sa stream is located mostly in residential areas with a partly closed canopy; the substrate was dominated by pebble and gravel, with few patches of leaf litter or dead wood (Fig. 
8A
). Mae Chaem wadeable river is kind of the submontane 
type
, bordered by farmland and residential areas; its substrate was dominated by sand (Fig. 
8B
). The larvae of the new species were found in the littoral zone, which was characterised by submerged wood, a sand and gravel bottom (Fig. 
8C
), and vegetation and roots along the riverbank (Fig. 
8D
).
